diff --git a/docs/RMBENCH_HELIOS.md b/docs/RMBENCH_HELIOS.md
new file mode 100644
index 0000000..d0e22e5
--- /dev/null
+++ b/docs/RMBENCH_HELIOS.md
@@ -0,0 +1,158 @@
+# RMBench Helios MemoryFastWAM
+
+This integration trains the local Helios-style FastWAM memory architecture directly from the official RMBench `demo_clean` HDF5 files and evaluates it with the official closed-loop simulator protocol.
+
+## Protocol
+
+The leaderboard contains nine tasks, each with 50 expert demonstrations and 100 expert-feasible evaluation rollouts:
+
+- `M(1)`: `observe_and_pickup`, `rearrange_blocks`, `put_back_block`, `swap_blocks`, `swap_T`
+- `M(n)`: `battery_try`, `blocks_ranking_try`, `cover_blocks`, `press_button`
+
+The downloaded dataset also contains `place_block_mat`, `classify_blocks`, and `storage_blocks`. They are intentionally excluded from the leaderboard run because they are not part of the paper's nine-task table. The training launcher creates one checkpoint per task, matching the paper's Execution Module single-task protocol. This differs from the current public Mem-0 release announced on 2026-07-14: its five M(1) tasks share one 50K-step `m1_mix` checkpoint, while its four M(n) tasks retain separate 30K-step checkpoints.
+
+Training reads each episode's `seen` instruction, matching the official policy preprocessing scripts. Closed-loop evaluation requests `unseen`. In the currently downloaded RMBench release the two strings happen to be identical for all 450 demonstrations, but the distinction is retained in manifests and receipts so a later data revision cannot silently leak evaluation language into training.
+
+## Data Contract
+
+The loader reads raw JPEG payloads and qpos vectors from each HDF5 episode without duplicating the dataset into another video tree.
+
+| Model field | RMBench source | Shape |
+| --- | --- | ---: |
+| global image | `observation/head_camera/rgb` | target composite top |
+| left wrist | `observation/left_camera/rgb` | target composite bottom-left |
+| right wrist | `observation/right_camera/rgb` | target composite bottom-right |
+| state | `joint_action/vector[t]` | source 14D -> canonical 80D |
+| action | `joint_action/vector[t+1]` | source 14D -> canonical 80D |
+
+The Aloha vector is `[left arm 6, left gripper, right arm 6, right gripper]`. Joint values map to canonical slots `14:20` and `21:27`; grippers map to slots `6` and `13`. The remaining 66 dimensions are zeroed and masked out in both diffusion and loss computation.
+
+Each sample is fixed to:
+
+```text
+state:  81 control points
+action: 80 next-qpos targets
+video:  21 frames at offsets 0,4,...,80
+memory: 8 + 2 + 1 frames strictly before the window start
+image:  3 x 21 x 384 x 320
+```
+
+At episode starts, unavailable history is left-padded with the current frame and marked invalid. A valid memory index is always less than `window_start`; target or future frames cannot enter memory.
+
+## Preparation
+
+```bash
+cd /public/interns/hubin/code/FastWAM
+
+/public/interns/hubin/code/hubin/miniforge3/envs/fastwam/bin/python3.10 \
+  scripts/rmbench/prepare_helios_memory_data.py \
+  --data-root /public/interns/hubin/dataset/RMBench/data \
+  --output-root /public/interns/hubin/dataset/RMBench/fastwam_helios \
+  --instruction-type seen
+```
+
+The current official preparation receipt contains 450 episodes, 277,350 frames, and 241,350 valid 81-frame windows. It writes only metadata, per-task canonical normalization, and text cache files under `fastwam_helios`; source images remain in the original HDF5 files. Its manifest SHA-256 is `e24fff6bf55e8f1041d55544c74d47ef8632c47d60fc5d8d04e6d2ae12dd6163`.
+
+Precompute all official task prompts once:
+
+```bash
+RMBENCH_HELIOS_ROOT=/public/interns/hubin/dataset/RMBench/fastwam_helios \
+/public/interns/hubin/code/hubin/miniforge3/envs/fastwam/bin/python3.10 \
+  scripts/precompute_text_embeds.py task=rmbench_helios_memory_finetune \
+  'data.train.tasks=[observe_and_pickup,rearrange_blocks,put_back_block,swap_blocks,swap_T,battery_try,blocks_ranking_try,cover_blocks,press_button]'
+```
+
+## Training
+
+One task:
+
+```bash
+bash scripts/rmbench/train_rmbench_helios.sh press_button 0 2500
+```
+
+Run the full suite with one task per available GPU:
+
+```bash
+python scripts/rmbench/launch_rmbench_helios_training.py \
+  --gpus 0,1,2,3,4,5,6,7 \
+  --steps 2500
+```
+
+The default initialization is the completed Tianji Helios-memory FastWAM checkpoint: 1,250 steps followed by a 1,250-step continuation, for 2,500 total self-data steps. It contains the canonical 80D action/proprio path and trained 8/2/1 memory patchers. Set `FASTWAM_RMBENCH_INIT` to use a different compatible MemoryFastWAM checkpoint. Each RMBench task then receives a separate 2,500-step fine-tune. This is not equivalent to Mem-0's reported 30K from-scratch iterations and that distinction must remain in result reports.
+
+Every 500 steps the trainer writes both a lightweight policy checkpoint and complete Accelerator state. The suite launcher reuses an existing final checkpoint, otherwise resumes from the newest valid optimizer/scheduler state. `--force` deliberately starts again from the Stage-2 initialization and may overwrite checkpoints with the same step number.
+
+## Closed-Loop Memory
+
+At evaluation, the current simulator observation is the FastWAM `input_image`. The server stores the preceding 11 real simulator observations and passes `history + current` to `MemoryFastWAM.infer_action`; the model's memory selector excludes the current frame. Generated video latents are never fed back as observations. For an eight-action execution chunk, GT observations are refreshed after action 4 and at the next replan after action 8. This matches the training video's four-control-step stride instead of rendering an unnecessary observation after every action.
+
+The policy predicts canonical 80D actions, applies the canonical invalid-dimension mask during diffusion, denormalizes with task-specific stats, and maps the 14 active values back to RMBench qpos order. It executes eight actions before replanning.
+
+The simulator and model run in separate environments because RMBench pins PyTorch 2.4.1 while FastWAM uses PyTorch 2.7.1. The H200 compute devices on this node do not expose Vulkan graphics queues to SAPIEN. `eval_rmbench_helios.sh` therefore renders through Mesa 26.1.5 lavapipe on CPU while CuRobo and FastWAM remain on the assigned CUDA device. The Helios evaluation wrapper defaults to SAPIEN's `default` raster camera shader. Mesa's CPU `rt` path remains selectable, but repeated native camera crashes make it unsuitable for the 9 x 100 local suite. OIDN also cannot be used because its CUDA interop requires the Vulkan render device to be CUDA-visible.
+
+Multiple SAPIEN RT clients can otherwise fail inside Mesa's native camera calls. The launcher gives every slot a separate XDG/tmp/shader-cache directory and limits lavapipe to one worker thread. The stable raster protocol leaves the cross-process render lock empty so all eight simulator/model pairs make progress concurrently. Selecting `RMBENCH_RENDER_SHADER=rt` enables the host-level lock by default around each complete `update_render -> take_picture -> get_picture` transaction, and callers can explicitly override the lock path. FastWAM does not consume camera calibration matrices, so the evaluation path also skips those native matrix reads while preserving all three RGB images, qpos, and camera layout.
+
+RMBench's bundled CuRobo v0.7.8 uses the legacy `wp.torch` namespace. Install
+`scripts/rmbench/requirements-eval-compat.txt` in the RMBench environment; it pins
+`warp-lang==1.8.0`. Newer Warp 1.15 removes that namespace and causes both planner
+workers to exit during setup. The evaluation shell checks this compatibility before
+starting either the simulator or model server.
+
+This renderer fallback is operationally necessary but is not pixel-equivalent to the official GPU ray-tracing environment. The evaluation receipts record raster versus ray-tracing pipeline, shader, applicable ray-tracing parameters, and Vulkan device; leaderboard tables must label this renderer difference.
+
+```bash
+bash scripts/rmbench/eval_rmbench_helios.sh \
+  press_button \
+  /public/interns/hubin/dataset/RMBench/fastwam_helios/runs/press_button/checkpoints/weights/step_002500.pt \
+  0
+```
+
+This invokes RMBench's official expert-seed filtering, unseen instruction setting, task step limit, and 100-rollout success-rate calculation.
+
+Before the full suite, run one end-to-end simulator rollout by setting `RMBENCH_EVAL_ROLLOUTS=1` on the same command. Probe and formal progress files are separate. During formal evaluation the client atomically records the next seed, completed rollout count, and successes after every rollout; a restart continues from that point. A suite task is marked successful only after its `100rollouts` progress reaches 100/100 and a matching result file exists.
+
+The progress identity includes the exact checkpoint, renderer pipeline and settings, camera-config policy, and GT observation stride. Raster receipts store ray-tracing-only fields as null. A changed pixel or temporal protocol cannot resume an older progress file; archive or remove that file before deliberately starting a new protocol.
+
+Run all nine task checkpoints in parallel, with both the FastWAM server and CuRobo
+simulator pinned to the assigned physical GPU. The full local 9 x 100 run explicitly
+selects the SAPIEN default raster pipeline. Ray-tracing samples, path depth, and denoiser
+do not apply to this pipeline:
+
+```bash
+RMBENCH_RENDER_SHADER=default \
+RMBENCH_LP_NUM_THREADS=1 \
+RMBENCH_SKIP_CAMERA_CONFIG=1 \
+RMBENCH_OBSERVATION_STRIDE=4 \
+python scripts/rmbench/launch_rmbench_helios_evaluation.py \
+  --gpus 0,1,2,3,4,5,6,7 \
+  --jobs-per-gpu 2 \
+  --max-attempts 20 \
+  --launch-stagger-seconds 20 \
+  --step 2500
+```
+
+Slots are assigned breadth-first: all eight GPUs receive one task before any GPU receives a
+second task. With nine tasks, only GPU 0 gets a second server. A measured server plus simulator
+uses about 29 GB on an H200, so two isolated jobs fit without sharing model state. Each slot has
+its own TCP port, log, progress receipt, result directory, and model process.
+
+The comparison report reads renderer settings from task receipts instead of assuming
+the defaults. Consequently, the resulting success rates are a closed-loop functional
+comparison under a lower-quality local renderer, not a pixel-equivalent reproduction
+of the official GPU-plus-OIDN benchmark.
+
+The launcher writes one resumable receipt per task under
+`fastwam_helios/evaluation/receipts`. A completed task is reused only when its
+receipt points to the same checkpoint and an existing official `_result.txt`.
+
+## Leaderboard
+
+Generate the comparison after all nine evaluations finish:
+
+```bash
+python scripts/rmbench/summarize_rmbench_results.py
+```
+
+The paper-table total averages are DP 5.8%, ACT 5.9%, Pi0.5 10.4%, X-VLA 9.8%, and Mem-0 42.0%. The current public Mem-0 release reports 56.6% on M(1) and 28.5% on M(n), or 44.1% across all nine tasks. The comparison script preserves both Mem-0 result sets, computes `M(1)`, `M(n)`, and total FastWAM averages, and writes both JSON and Markdown receipts. Helios uses only 2,500 task-specific fine-tune steps and a different architecture, so neither column is a budget-matched comparison.
+
+Sources: [RMBench project](https://rmbench.github.io/), [paper](https://arxiv.org/abs/2603.01229), [official repository](https://github.com/robotwin-Platform/rmbench), [current M(1) release](https://huggingface.co/qiuly/Mem-0-m1mix-RMBench), and [current M(n) release](https://huggingface.co/qiuly/Mem-0-mn-RMBench).
